{"kind":"notes","id":"nt/salf5u","slide":2,"text":"The urgency is simple: India meets about 88 percent of its crude needs through imports. A disruption is not just a news event; it becomes a procurement, route, refinery, and cost decision. Today those threads are often separated—signals in one place, alternatives in another, approvals elsewhere. The consequence is slower, more reactive timing when the market is least forgiving.\n\nTransition: The issue is not a lack of data. It is that generic tools overlook the physics and accountability of the decision."}
